One would have expected, for example, that from the 2013 elections onwards, the electorate would choose leaders on the basis of their pledges to reduce poverty levels by, say, three per cent, during their five-year tenure in their wards, constituencies and counties, respectively. It is here that the role of education comes in.
Educational qualifications
During the campaigns, the candidates liberally parade their educational qualifications in order to impress the electorate. It is assumed, therefore, that these candidates will use the qualifications to formulate policies and work towards attracting investors in their electoral areas to reduce poverty. 
This should be more applicable to the governor and those individuals who will be assigned devolved functions, such as agriculture and water development.
 I have no training in agriculture, but let me share my experiences. First, when I attended an agricultural show in Paris, I was amazed that farmers from the Sahel countries of Mali, Burkina Faso, Cote d’Ivoire and Senegal were exhibiting and selling dry land crops such as tamarind and gooseberry juices.



