All these crops are just but a few of the many crops that grow especially in the arid and semi-arid areas. The governors and their advisers have not paid much attention to work towards exploiting these God-given crops, as is the case in the Sahel countries, Israel and Equatorial countries like Colombia.
In the early 1960s, a French agronomist, Rene Dumont, lamented that agriculture in Africa was taking a false start soon after Independence. Are we witnessing another “false start” in some counties 60 years after the assertion by Mr Dumont?
There may be a strong case for the mindsets of the educated county bosses to be rebooted to think local and act global. Or didn’t their education enable them to focus on opportunities to lift their people out of excruciating poverty through innovative practices?
